{{redirect|Henry Weaver|the Pittsburgh mayor|Henry A. Weaver}} '''Henry Grady Weaver''' (December 24, 1889 – January 3, 1949) was the director of Customer Research Staff for [[General Motors Corporation]], and shown on the cover of the November 14, 1938 issue of [[Time Magazine]]. He is credited with developing the use of the survey questionnaire to investigate customer preferences for design features in cars.
==Early life and education== He was named after, but not related to, [[Henry Woodfin Grady]] who died the year before Weaver was born. He was nicknamed Buck Weaver after the baseball player of the same name who later was part of the 1919 [[Black Sox scandal]].<ref name="time">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,772072,00.html|title=Thought-Starter|date=1938-11-14|publisher=[[Time Magazine]]|accessdate=2011-07-09}}</ref> He was born in [[Eatonton, Georgia]] and obtained his Bachelor of Science from [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] in 1911.<ref name="time"/>
==Career== Blind in his right eye since birth, he worked as a mechanic, salesman and draftsman before becoming director of Customer Research Staff of [[General Motors Corporation]]. It was for that work that he was placed on the cover of the November 14, 1938 issue of ''[[Time magazine|Time]]''.
He is best known for his work, ''[[The Mainspring of Human Progress]]''.
