'''Warren Brown''' (1929 – 25 December 2014) was a [[Bermuda|Bermudian]] sailor and businessman. He took part in the [[Bermuda Race|Newport-Bermuda Race]] 20 times in 11 different boats, including four of his own. He was also a co-founder of the Island Press, which produced the now defunct ''[[Bermuda Sun]]'' newspaper.<ref>{{cite news|title=The world: Through Warren Brown’s eyes|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20140619/ISLAND/140619731|publisher=[[The Royal Gazette (Bermuda)|The Royal Gazette]]|date=19 June 2014|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref><ref name="Death">{{cite news|title=Sailing pioneer Warren Brown dies|url=http://www.royalgazette.com/article/20141226/NEWS/141229874|publisher=[[The Royal Gazette (Bermuda)|The Royal Gazette]]|date=26 December 2014|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref>
==Personal life== Brown, at three months old, was among those who survived a shipwreck on 18 December 1929, when the [[RMS Fort Victoria|RMS ''Fort Victoria'']] was rammed by the [[USAHS Algonquin|SS ''Algonquin'']] while anchored in dense fog.<ref name="Death" /> All aboard the ''Fort Victoria'' were rescued before she sank.<ref>{{cite book | first =Keith | last =Eastlake | year =1998 | month = | title =Sea Disasters, the truth behind the tragedies | pages =20 | publisher =Greenwich Editions | location =London N7 |isbn=0-86288-149-8 }}</ref>
